<h1>Pathogenic Pulmonary Disease (PPD)</h1>

<p>
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_disease_2019">COVID-19</a>
is caused by a new strain of
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus">coronavirus</a>.
But COVID-19 is very much a type of danger that has always been around.
COVID-19 is a "Pathogenic Pulmonary Disease" (PPD), along with
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Influenza">influenza</a>,
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pneumonia">pneumonia</a>, and
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuberculosis">tuberculosis</a>.
These PPDs have caused deaths every year, year-round, for millennia.
</p>

{#
<h3>A Future of Dangers Past</h3>
<p>
Many dangers have been reduced decade after decade, in a clear general trend
of progress.
This is true for Pathogenic Pulmonary Diseases in the USA since the late 1800s.
A simple and practical rough measure of average danger from Pathogenic
Pulmonary Diseases is <em>weekly deaths per million</em>.
</p>

Past danger levels of Pathogenic Pulmonary Diseases provide
context to think about your danger level during the 2020 pandemic.
Consider how many decades into the past would you need to retrogress
to live in a comparable level of danger from Pathogenic Pulmonary Disease.

